# Git Workflow

## Branch Strategy

- **One task = one branch.** At the START of a task, branch off the latest main:
  `git switch main && git pull && git switch -c <type>/<short-task-name>`.
- **Stay on that branch for the whole task** — no branch-hopping mid-task.
- **Never reuse a branch after its PR has merged.** Start a fresh one off main.
- Each parallel agent works on its OWN branch (and ideally its own git worktree)
  so uncommitted work can't collide.

## Commit Guidelines

- Commit frequently to your own branch, with descriptive messages.
- Commit only your own files via explicit paths (`git commit -- <paths>`);
  never `git add -A` / `commit -a` — it sweeps up other agents' work.
- Use conventional commit style when appropriate.

## Opening a PR

- Open ONE pull request per branch, at the END of the task, once it's verified
  (typecheck + relevant tests pass).
- Before opening/merging, sync onto latest main: `git fetch && git rebase origin/main`,
  resolve any conflicts on your branch, then `git push --force-with-lease`.
- After it merges (squash is fine — the branch is never reused), delete the branch.

## Never

- Never force-push main or any shared branch. `--force-with-lease` is only OK on
  your own feature branch after a rebase.
- Never push directly to main (the human owner does that deliberately).
